article.description:
Returning from a nine-game absence with a bruised left foot,
David Wesley scored 17 points as the Hornets took a 100-81 victory Wednesday night to avenge a 79-76 loss at Cleveland four days ago.
article.headline: Back from injury, Wesley leads Hornets past Cavs
article.linkText: Wesley returns to help Hornets get back at Cavs
article.story:
NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Getting David Wesley back in the lineup made the New Orleans Hornets look like a different team against the Cleveland Cavaliers. Returning from a nine-game absence with a bruised left foot, Wesley scored 17 points as the Hornets took a 100-81 victory Wednesday night to avenge a 79-76 loss at Cleveland four days ago. Wesley's outside game forced Cleveland out of its zone defense, which seemed to create more space for Jamal Mashburn. He scored a game-high 28 points, 14 in the third quarter, and is averaging 24 points over his last 10 games. "Even though I've been out nine games, my guy didn't (drop down to double-team Mashburn), so Mash was able to wheel and deal and do his thing,'' Wesley said. "I felt I played a decent game. I'm trying to push through the pain, trying to ignore it.'' The Hornets needed the victory to maintain their tenuous hold on the fifth playoff seed in the Eastern Conference, as Boston, which trails New Orleans by a game, won in Washington. In Saturday's loss to Cleveland, New Orleans was without starters Baron Davis (left knee), P.J. Brown (right ankle) and Wesley. Brown and Davis, who are day-to-day, missed Wednesday's game. Wesley scored the first points of the game on his first shot -- a 17 foot jumper -- and the Hornets never trailed. They led by as much as 30 near the end of the third quarter. Wesley also had eight assists. "He comes in and gives them a spark shooting the ball,'' Cavaliers guard Ricky Davis said. "He distributes the ball well. He knows the game.'' George Lynch had 12 points and a season-high 14 rebounds, while Jamaal Magloire added 14 points and 10 rebounds. New Orleans outshot Cleveland 50 percent to 38.6 percent and outrebounded the Cavaliers 50-41. Reserve Jumaine Jones scored 21 to lead Cleveland, which has lost seven of eight games. Zydrunas Ilgauskas added 15 points and Carlos Boozer 10, while Diop DeSagana grabbed 11 rebounds. Starting with Davis' layup at the third-quarter buzzer, Cleveland used a 12-0 run to close to 87-69. The run agitated Hornets coach Paul Silas, who told three starters to check in. Suddenly, the Hornets' second unit turned it around, scoring six straight points and prompting Silas to send the starters back to the bench. "I scared 'em,'' Silas said with a smile as he glanced at the sideline press table. New Orleans took an 18-6 lead when Mashburn hit a 3-pointer to cap a 9-0 run and a stint of six straight Hornets possessions with a field goal. "It was imperative for us to come out with some energy and shore up some things,'' Mashburn said. "I'm glad to have David back. He gave us some quality points -- got his game rhythm back a little. If we can continue to get healthy and get right at the right time, we can go on a heck of a run.'' The Hornets pushed the lead up to 40-19 with eight minutes left in the first half when Jerome Moiso soared along the baseline to dunk Mashburn's miss, capping a 10-0 run. Cleveland got as close as 47-34 with a 10-3 run that ended with a reverse layup by Miles and Ilgauskas' putback of a missed free throw. The Hornets then built the lead back up to 18 before Jones hit a 3 at the halftime buzzer, leaving the score 57-42. "This was probably one of our worst game in a while,'' Cleveland coach Keith Smart said. "This team was ready for us. Wesley makes a big difference.''

Game notes
The Cavs have lost 19 straight road games and are 3-36 away from Cleveland. The last road victory came Jan. 12 at Seattle. ... The Cavaliers, who lost to Washington on Tuesday night, are 4-19 in the second of back-to-back games. ... Mashburn made 12 of 17 shots. ... New Orleans had gone 4-5 without Wesley. ... Stacey Augmon got his second start of the season, filling in at shooting guard. He scored eight points and had five assists in 29 minutes, while helping hold Cleveland's Davis to nine points. ... New Orleans is 19-0 when scoring 100 or more at home.
